{{notability|date=September 2018}}
'''LZJB''' is a [[lossless data compression]] [[algorithm]] invented by [[Jeff Bonwick]] to compress [[crash dump]]s and data in [[ZFS]]. The software is [[Common Development and Distribution License|CDDL]] [[Software|license licensed]]. It includes a number of improvements to the [[LZRW|LZRW1]] algorithm, a member of the [[LZ77 and LZ78|Lempel–Ziv]] family of compression algorithms.<ref>{{Cite journal|author=Y. Rathore, M. Ahirwar, R. Pandey|title=A Brief Study of Data Compression Algorithms|URL=https://www.academia.edu/11814232/A_Brief_Study_of_Data_Compression_Algorithms|publisher=Journal of Computer Science IJCSIS|year=2013|volume=11|issue=10|pages=90|issn=}}</ref>. The name LZJB is derived from its parent algorithm and its creator—Lempel Ziv Jeff Bonwick. Bonwick is also one of two architects of ZFS, and the creator of the [[Slab allocation|Slab Allocator]].

